Untitled Page 5

The reason the entries this year are so poor in handwriting
is not entirely due to age as may
be expected. The poor quality of
paper necessitates a light pressure
on the pen; this cramps my usual style.

Monday, January 1, 1945

This is the day I finally decided
to consider the northern subspecies
Arizona E. blanchardi and the
southern arizona E. Elegans. I wonder
whether time will eventually show
this to have been good judgement.
Spent nearly the entire day and
evening recalculating the statistics
of blanchardi and elegans because
of the near allocations and
arrangements.

Friday, March 23, 1945

Spent the day at Stanford. Drove
back with Paul in the late afternoon.
Worked over their rattlers in the
mornings checking oreganus tail
marks.
Went to lunch with Myers, Wiggins
(the botanist) Lieut Herald. Spent the
afternoon discussing Myers experiences
in Brazil, Herald's in the south west Pacific
etc. A very interesting afternoon

Friday, June 1,. 1945

This morning Weiss and I went
to the mesquite hammocks 17 mi. E. of
El Centro 7:20 to 8:30. A fine warm
morning. No sidewinder or atox tracks
although we hunted quite a while. Only
me you'd seen - a Mma, 34 miles
almost all irrigated.
Went to El Centro in business;
drove too fast to check anything.
Left El Centro at 11:30; it was
quite wrm. Drove too fast to
check snakes and I only drove to Jacumba anyway. Did see a large
DOR gopher at mobile. Fields
Reached home at 3:00 P.M.

Saturday, July 7, 1945

Put in a long day and evening
on the rattler habitats paper. Some
letters; some bibliographic work. Went
over some of the past letters.
I had a long talk with Mrs.
Benchley this morning about the
increased scope and size of the
paper -- probably run at least
300 pages -- and one is still
willing and anxious to publish it.
Also talked over the press of clerical,
stenographic, and copy work.
She was quite willing to hire a
girl to do it. All this is very
encouraging indeed.
Van A hyman called on the
phone today.

Monday, August 20, 1945

This afternoon with Phil + GG
went out in teh back country.
Started at 3:50. Clear + hot. Went
out via the highway to Deserneo
Cuyarance, then down the
Banner grade to Scissors Crossing.
Daylight drive 75 miles; only one
DOR seen
1 Red Racer M DOR Banner Brush.
Hung around scissors crossing
waiting for it to get dark. It was
quite comfortable 81 degrees and breezy.
then drove out beyond the
Narrows and back. Not a snake
was seen alive or dead -
Reached the Narrows at 8:18 82 degrees almost dark
Turned back 7 miles east of the
Narrows 8:45 93 degrees F.
Got 2 Colony x
1 2 mi. W. of Narrows
1 1 " E " "
Also a Uta Sans COR at Sentenac
Bridge. 9:45. Turned it loose.
Reached Scissors Crossing at 9:55. 82 degrees F
Cool + breezy.
Total ? drove 38 miles 2 1/2 hrs/ Nearly
full moon. Another proof that it isn't the
temperature, but the season that controls.
